arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.

Locus 102 is the raised floor resting on dirt in the west of the hypocaust room against Locus 76. It consists of two reused hexagonal pavers from the Lower Temenos and seven rough-hewn sandstone pavers. The floor level is 12 cm above the main floor of the hypocaust room (Locus 42), and is flush with the threshold of the doorway between the hypocaust room and the southwest room (Locus 77). The floor also surrounds Locus 103, the single large hewn ashlar against Locus 76 that is possibly a bench. The pavers are not lined up in any coherent way, and are of various sizes and shapes. Most important are the two reused hexagonal pavers. These were robbed out from the Lower Temenos and reused here, establishing the later date of the floor, and demonstrating most vividly the resourcefulness of the builders (or remodelers) of the bath complex. Importantly, the hexagonal pavers establish this locus and the associated features of this stage as post-363. The hexagonal pavers could only reasonably be robbed out after that part of the Great Temple was in ruined, which is dated to the 363 earthquake. South of these hexagonal pavers there is compacted soil (Locus 86) that has not been fully excavated, so it is unknown if the main floor of the hypocaust room continues below. This floor is enigmatic, as its function is quite unclear. Why would an additional floor be necessary when there was a better-made one already in existence? With no clean edge to the floor, especially to the north and west, this floors appears very clumsy and disorganized. Clearly later than the original floor of the hypocaust room, the raised floor is phased to Stage 4, the period of reconfiguration of the complex.
2.96 m north south -by- 0.83 m east west.
